    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Enhance stealth capabilities using Camoufox built-in options and Playwright preNavigationHooks\n**Description**: Modify src/main.ts to randomize viewport, force timezone/locale, block noise resources, and enable humanize cursor movement. Update the integration test to verify crawling still works.\n## All Steps\n1. **Randomize headless mode and viewport size**: ## Goal\nModify `src/main.ts` to enhance stealth by randomizing the browser viewport dimensions and enabling Camoufox's virtual headless mode. This reduces fingerprinting consistency across requests.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification in `src/main.ts` – update the `camoufoxLaunchOptions()` call and add a viewport randomization utility.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- File: `src/main.ts` lines 44-57 contain `PlaywrightCrawler` creation. Specifically, lines 50-55:\n  ```ts\n  const launchOptions = await camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n      headless: true,\n      proxy: await proxyConfiguration?.newUrl(),\n      geoip: true,\n  });\n  ```\n- `camoufoxLaunchOptions` expects `LaunchOptions` from `camoufox-js` (v0.9.3), which supports:\n  - `window: [number, number]` – fixed window size\n  - `headless: boolean | \"virtual\"` – `\"virtual\"` enables a virtual display (Xvfb) for complete headless masking\n- No viewport randomization currently exists; viewport is browser default.\n- Camoufox's built-in stealth already spoofs many fingerprints, but a fixed viewport is less realistic.\n- The Docker base image `apify/actor-node-playwright-camoufox:24-1.60.0` includes Xvfb, so `headless: \"virtual\"` will work.\n\n## Action\n1. Create a constant array of common desktop viewport sizes (width × height) in `src/main.ts` before the crawler creation.\n2. Add a function `getRandomViewport()` that picks a random pair from the array.\n3. Modify the `camoufoxLaunchOptions()` call to:\n   - Set `window` to the randomly chosen dimensions.\n   - Change `headless` from `true` to `\"virtual\"`.\n4. Ensure the viewport is randomized once per crawl run (not per page) by calling `getRandomViewport()` before the crawler constructor.\n5. If `headless: \"virtual\"` causes issues in certain environments (e.g., CI without Xvfb), fall back to `headless: true` with a log warning.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Randomizing viewport mimics real user diversity, making automation harder to detect.\n- `headless: \"virtual\"` uses a virtual display, so the browser thinks it has a real screen (no `navigator.webdriver` flags). Camoufox already hides headless, but virtual mode adds another layer.\n- Using Camoufox's built-in `window` option, not Playwright's `setViewportSize`, because Camoufox must apply its fingerprint adjustments at launch.\n- Keeping the random pick at crawler start (not per page) avoids recomputing launch options mid-session, which is unsupported.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- In `src/main.ts`, after imports and before `Actor.init()`, add:\n  ```ts\n  const COMMON_VIEWPORTS: [number, number][] = [\n      [1920, 1080],\n      [1366, 768],\n      [1440, 900],\n      [1536, 864],\n      [1280, 720],\n  ];\n\n  function getRandomViewport(): [number, number] {\n      return COMMON_VIEWPORTS[Math.floor(Math.random() * COMMON_VIEWPORTS.length)];\n  }\n  ```\n- Replace lines 50-55 with:\n  ```ts\n  const viewport = getRandomViewport();\n  const headlessMode = process.env.HEADLESS_VIRTUAL !== 'false' ? 'virtual' as const : true;\n  const launchOptions = await camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n      headless: headlessMode,\n      window: viewport,\n      proxy: await proxyConfiguration?.newUrl(),\n      geoip: true,\n  });\n  log.info(`Using viewport ${viewport[0]}×${viewport[1]} and headless mode: ${headlessMode}`);\n  ```\n- The environment variable `HEADLESS_VIRTUAL` (set to `'false'`) allows overriding for CI or environments without Xvfb.\n- No changes to `useIncognitoPages` or other options.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `headless: \"virtual\"` is used and Xvfb is missing, Camoufox will throw at launch. The catch block around crawler creation (if any) should handle it. If not present, we add a try-catch around `crawler.run()` with a fallback to `headless: true` after logging the error.\n- Viewport randomization must be deterministic per run; using `Math.random()` is fine because each run gets a fresh seed.\n- If proxy is not available (null), we still proceed without proxy – viewport randomization still applies.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm run start:dev` (or `apify run`) locally. The log should show the chosen viewport and headless mode.\n- Crawl https://apify.com and verify that pages load correctly, no errors due to viewport/headless change.\n- Run `npm test` to ensure existing integration test (which crawls apify.com) still passes.\n- Optionally inspect browser fingerprints via a detection site (e.g., fingerprintjs.com) to confirm viewport is non-default.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- No new npm packages.\n- Input schema unchanged – stealth is internal.\n- The environment variable `HEADLESS_VIRTUAL` can be set in `.actor/actor.json` under `environmentVariables` for CI, but not required.\n\n## Constraints\n- Viewport must be set via `window` in launchOptions, not via Playwright's `page.setViewportSize()` after launch – Camoufox's fingerprinting depends on it.\n- Randomization occurs once at crawler start; per-crawl-run randomness is sufficient.\n- Must maintain compatibility with the existing proxy and geoip setup.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- No impact on dataset output or router.\n- Crawler behavior unchanged – still uses same `preNavigationHooks` (not modified in this step).\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- Viewport randomization adds negligible overhead.\n- `headless: \"virtual\"` may use slightly more memory due to virtual display, but acceptable for typical runs.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- Add a comment in `src/main.ts` explaining the viewport randomization and virtual headless mode.\n- Optionally update `README.md` if present, but not required.\n2. **Force timezone and locale via Camoufox env**: ## Goal\nModify the Camoufox launch configuration to force a specific locale (`it-IT`) and timezone (`Europe/Rome`) to enhance stealth consistency with the IT proxy.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification in `src/main.ts`. No new dependencies.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- Relevant file: `src/main.ts`, lines 48–56 currently contain:\n```ts\nconst launchOptions = await camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n    headless: true,\n    proxy: await proxyConfiguration?.newUrl(),\n    geoip: true,\n});\n```\n- Camoufox `LaunchOptions` (from `node_modules/camoufox-js/dist/utils.d.ts`):\n  - `locale?: string | string[]` — forces locale for Intl API (e.g. `\"it-IT\"`)\n  - `env?: Record<string, string | number | boolean>` — sets environment variables; `TZ` is used to set timezone (e.g. `{ TZ: 'Europe/Rome' }`)\n  - `geoip: true` already enables IP-based geolocation (includes timezone), but forcing via env ensures consistency even if proxy fails.\n- The `add-headless-viewport-randomization` step (already completed) has added `headless` and `window`/`screen` randomization. This step builds on that.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Locate the `camoufoxLaunchOptions` call.\n3. Add `locale: \"it-IT\"` to the options object.\n4. Add `env: { TZ: 'Europe/Rome' }` to the options object.\n5. Ensure that the existing properties (`headless`, `proxy`, `geoip`, `window`, `screen`) are preserved and not overwritten.\n\n## Reasoning\n- The proxy is configured with `countryCode: 'IT'`, so forcing Italian locale and European/Rome timezone makes the browser fingerprint consistent with the IP location.\n- Using `env.TZ` is the most reliable way to set timezone in Firefox (Camoufox spawns Firefox with this environment variable).\n- `locale` influences `navigator.language`, `Intl.DateTimeFormat`, etc., which are commonly checked by anti-bot systems.\n- This step requires no additional imports or dependencies.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- Insert the new properties after `geoip: true` (order does not matter).\n- The resulting `launchOptions` object should look like:\n```ts\nconst launchOptions = await camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n    headless: true,  // or \"virtual\" after randomization step\n    proxy: await proxyConfiguration?.newUrl(),\n    geoip: true,\n    locale: \"it-IT\",\n    env: { TZ: 'Europe/Rome' },\n    window: [randomWidth, randomHeight],  // added in previous step\n    screen: { ... }  // added in previous step\n});\n```\n- Use double quotes for the string values.\n- Ensure `locale` is a single string, not an array (Camoufox accepts both).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `proxyConfiguration?.newUrl()` throws (e.g. no proxy configured), the `TZ` env and `locale` still apply, providing a consistent fallback fingerprint.\n- Do not assume `env` already exists; this step creates it fresh.\n- Do not change any other parts of the configuration.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm run build` to ensure no TypeScript errors.\n- Run the existing integration test (`npm test`) to verify crawling still works.\n- Optionally, run a quick local crawl with debug logging to see if `navigator.language` returns `\"it-IT\"` and `Intl.DateTimeFormat().resolvedOptions().timeZone` returns `\"Europe/Rome\"` (can be added temporarily in a handler).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on `add-headless-viewport-randomization` being completed (the `launchOptions` object already has `headless`, `window`, `screen` modifications).\n- No external dependencies.\n- Input: none; the locale/timezone is hardcoded to match the IT proxy.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not remove or override `geoip: true`; it provides additional IP-based fingerprinting.\n- Keep the code clean and consistent with existing style (single quotes for strings? The project uses double quotes in import statements but code uses backticks or double quotes; follow the existing pattern in `main.ts`).\n- Do not introduce any new environment variables or configuration files.\n- This step must not break the `headless`, `window`, or `screen` settings added in the previous step.\n3. **Block trackers/analytics via preNavigationHooks**: ## Goal\nAdd a `preNavigationHooks` array to the PlaywrightCrawler configuration in `src/main.ts` to block network requests targeting common trackers, analytics, and other noise, while preserving resources that aid stealth (e.g., fonts, scripts).\n\n## Task Type\nConfiguration & Code Modification — Add a new option to an existing crawler constructor call.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/main.ts` (63 lines), lines 44–57 contain the `PlaywrightCrawler` instantiation.\n- **Existing options**: `launchContext`, `proxyConfiguration`, `maxRequestsPerCrawl`, `useSessionPool`, `sessionPoolOptions`.\n- **PlaywrightCrawler constructor** (`@crawlee/playwright`) accepts `preNavigationHooks?: PlaywrightHook[]`. A PlaywrightHook is `(crawlingContext, gotoOptions) => Promise<void>`, where `crawlingContext.page` is a Playwright `Page`.\n- **Camoufox launchOptions** already block some noise via `block_images`? Currently not set. This step will NOT use Camoufox's `block_*` flags; instead uses Playwright's `page.route()` for flexible blocking at the request level.\n- **Domain list** (concrete, non-exhaustive): `doubleclick.net`, `google-analytics.com`, `googletagmanager.com`, `facebook.net`, `facebook.com/tr`, `amazon-adsystem.com`, `scorecardresearch.com`, `hotjar.com`, `mouseflow.com`, `newrelic.com`. Allow all others, including fonts.gstatic.com, cdn.jsdelivr.net, etc.\n\n## Action\nIn `src/main.ts`, locate the `new PlaywrightCrawler({...})` call (around line 44). Add a new property `preNavigationHooks` with a single hook function that sets up a request handler via `page.route('**/*')`. Inside the handler, block URLs matching a curated set of tracker/analytics patterns. Allow all other requests to continue normally.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Blocking trackers reduces unnecessary network traffic, speeds up page loads, and avoids being flagged by anti-bot services that detect known analytics calls.\n- Using `preNavigationHooks` instead of Camoufox `block_*` flags gives finer control: we can keep stealth-friendly resources (fonts, scripts) while dropping ads/trackers.\n- The hook is executed once per navigation (when page is created), so it applies to all requests on that page.\n\n## Implementation Details\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Before the crawler options object, define a helper function or constant for the pattern array:\n   ```typescript\n   const BLOCKED_PATTERNS = [\n       /doubleclick\\.net/,\n       /google-analytics\\.com/,\n       /googletagmanager\\.com/,\n       /facebook\\.net/,\n       /amazon-adsystem\\.com/,\n       /scorecardresearch\\.com/,\n       /hotjar\\.com/,\n       /mouseflow\\.com/,\n       /newrelic\\.com/,\n       // Add more patterns as needed\n   ];\n   ```\n3. Inside the crawler options, add:\n   ```typescript\n   preNavigationHooks: [\n       async ({ page }) => {\n           await page.route('**/*', async (route) => {\n               const url = route.request().url();\n               const shouldBlock = BLOCKED_PATTERNS.some(pattern => pattern.test(url));\n               if (shouldBlock) {\n                   await route.abort('blockedbyclient');\n               } else {\n                   await route.continue();\n               }\n           });\n       },\n   ],\n   ```\n4. Ensure the hook is placed **before** any other options that might rely on page navigation (e.g., `launchContext` is already before).\n5. Import `Page` type from `playwright` if needed (but the hook signature infers it).\n6. No changes to other files required.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- **Route abort failures**: If `route.abort()` throws (e.g., page closed), catch silently to avoid breaking navigation.\n- **Pattern matching**: Use case-insensitive or ensure patterns work on full URLs. Patterns like `/google-analytics\\.com/` will match both HTTP and HTTPS.\n- **Very large number of blocked requests**: Not a problem; Playwright handles aborting efficiently.\n- **If `preNavigationHooks` is undefined**: Adding it is safe; if the crawler option is not supported in older versions? It is present in `@crawlee/playwright` v3.x. Verify the installed version: `@crawlee/playwright` ^3.15.3 (package.json). This version supports `preNavigationHooks`.\n- **CSS and fonts that are required for rendering**: They are **not** blocked; only domains listed above are blocked.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm run build` to ensure TypeScript compilation passes.\n- Run `npm test` (vitest) — the existing integration test crawls `apify.com` and should still succeed. Logs should show no errors from blocked requests.\n- Optionally add a quick unit test that verifies the hook function exists and blocks known patterns (but not required for this step).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Assumes `add-headless-viewport-randomization` step (viewport and headless changes) is already implemented, as the crawler options object is expanded.\n- No new npm packages.\n- Input schema unchanged.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not block requests that are essential for page functionality or anti-bot fingerprinting (e.g., Google Fonts, standard CDN scripts).\n- Do not modify `routes.ts`, `test/main.test.ts`, or other files.\n- Keep the pattern list concise; future steps can extend it.\n- The hook must be efficient — `page.route` is called once, then Playwright intercepts automatically.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- The crawler will still function identically for external consumers; no API changes.\n- The integration test remains valid.\n- No impact on output schema or dataset.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- Blocking requests reduces overall bandwidth and CPU usage (fewer network requests per page).\n- `route.abort` is lightweight; there is no noticeable overhead.\n- Minimal memory footprint.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- If an internal comment block exists describing stealth enhancements, add a line about blocked domains (optional).\n\n## Diagram\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    A[preNavigationHook] -->|page.route| B{Request URL matches BLOCKED_PATTERNS?}\n    B -->|Yes| C[route.abort]\n    B -->|No| D[route.continue]\n```\n4. **Enable native humanize cursor movement**: ## Goal\nEnable Camoufox's built-in human-like cursor movement to further reduce bot detection. The option randomizes mouse movements with configurable delay (default up to 1.5 seconds).\n\n## Task Type\nImplementation – modify existing configuration code in `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/main.ts` (lines 44–57 currently define `launchContext.launchOptions` via `camoufoxLaunchOptions()`)\n- **Camoufox LaunchOptions interface** (from `camoufox-js/dist/utils.d.ts`): includes `humanize?: boolean | number` – if `true`, delays mouse movements up to 1.5s; if a number `n`, delays up to `n` seconds.\n- **Current launchOptions** (lines 50–55 in `src/main.ts`) contain: `headless: true`, `proxy: proxyUrl`, `geoip: true`. No `humanize`.\n- **No new npm packages** – `humanize` is already available in `camoufox-js@0.9.3`.\n- **Dependency chain**: This step runs after viewport randomization is added (step `add-headless-viewport-randomization`), so the viewport randomizer function and `window`/`screen` options are already present.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Locate the object passed to `camoufoxLaunchOptions()` inside `launchContext`.\n3. Add the property `humanize: true` to that object. (Optionally use `humanize: 1.5` to be explicit about max delay.)\n4. Ensure no syntax errors; the object already ends after `geoip: true`, so a comma must be added.\n5. Run `npm run build` to confirm TypeScript compiles without errors.\n6. Run `npm test` to verify the integration test still passes.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Camoufox's built-in `humanize` option is the simplest and most maintainable way to simulate realistic mouse movement. It avoids custom Playwright scripts or external libraries.\n- The delay is bounded (default 0–1.5s), so it won't significantly impact crawl speed.\n- This is a pure configuration addition with zero risk of breaking existing crawl logic.\n\n## Implementation Details\nIn `src/main.ts`, change the launchOptions call from:\n```typescript\nlaunchOptions: camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n    headless: true,\n    proxy: proxyUrl,\n    geoip: true,\n})\n```\nto:\n```typescript\nlaunchOptions: camoufoxLaunchOptions({\n    headless: true,\n    proxy: proxyUrl,\n    geoip: true,\n    humanize: true,   // <-- add this\n})\n```\n(If viewport randomization has already been added, there will be additional properties like `window`, `screen`, etc.; the `humanize` line should be inserted after `geoip: true` but before the closing `}`.)\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- No runtime errors expected. The `humanize` option is validated by Camoufox itself; invalid types cause warnings in Camoufox logs (but not crashes).\n- If the option is accidentally mistyped (e.g. `humanize: 'true'`), TypeScript will catch it because the interface expects `boolean | number | undefined`.\n- The feature works in both headless and headed modes; no Docker configuration change needed.\n\n## Validation\n- **Compilation**: `npm run build` should succeed with no new errors.\n- **Lint**: `npm run lint` should pass (no style changes).\n- **Test**: `npm test` – the existing integration test (`test/main.test.ts`) must still pass:\n    1. Crawls at least one page from `https://apify.com`.\n    2. Pushes dataset items with `title` and `url` fields.\n    3. Dataset item count equals requested maxRequestsPerCrawl.\n- **Manual verification (optional)**: Add a temporary `log.info` to print the launchOptions object and confirm `humanize: true` appears.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Inputs from previous steps**: The `add-headless-viewport-randomization` step must have already created the random viewport utility and added `window`/`screen` to launchOptions. This step only appends the `humanize` property.\n- **No additional npm installs or Docker changes**.\n\n## Constraints\n- Must not alter the functionality of the crawler (routing, enqueuing, extraction).\n- Must preserve ESM import style (`.js` extensions) and TypeScript strict mode.\n- Must not introduce new dependencies.\n- The change must be minimal and reversible.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- No changes to input schema, output schema, or actor API surface.\n- The Crawlee `PlaywrightCrawler` remains unchanged; only browser launch options differ.\n- Post-step integration test ensures the crawl still completes successfully.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- `humanize: true` adds a small delay per mouse action (up to 1.5s). In a typical crawl with few clicks (the current `routes.ts` does not perform any clicks), the impact is negligible.\n- If the actor later adds interaction-heavy logic, the delay may compound – but for now it's safe.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- No documentation update required (stealth enhancements are internal). Optionally, a comment `// humanize: enable realistic mouse movement` can be added.\n5. **Update integration test to verify stealth enhancements**: ## Goal\nUpdate the existing Vitest integration test (`test/main.test.ts`) to validate that the stealth enhancements (randomized viewport, forced timezone/locale, resource blocking via `preNavigationHooks`, and native humanize cursor movement) do not break the basic crawling functionality.\n\n## Task Type\nModify test file – add assertions and possibly a new test case to verify stealth options are applied correctly.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File to modify**: `test/main.test.ts` (27 lines currently)\n- **Current test**: Uses `vitest`, `purgeDefaultStorages()` in `beforeAll`, creates a `RequestList` from `[https://apify.com]`, runs `crawler.run()`, and expects dataset items to have `url` and `title` properties.\n- **Crawler setup**: The test imports the main crawler configuration (via `main.ts`) which after previous steps now includes:\n  - `headless: true` (or `\"virtual\"`)\n  - Randomized viewport via `window: [randomWidth, randomHeight]`\n  - `locale: \"it-IT\"`, `env: { TZ: \"Europe/Rome\" }`\n  - `preNavigationHooks` that block tracker/analytics domains (e.g., `google-analytics.com`, `doubleclick.net`)\n  - `humanize: true` in `camoufoxLaunchOptions()`\n- **Existing test structure**:\n  ```typescript\n  import { describe, it, beforeAll } from 'vitest';\n  import { purgeDefaultStorages } from '@crawlee/core';\n  import { Actor } from 'apify';\n  // ... existing imports and test\n  ```\n- **Camoufox API**: The stealth options are applied via `camoufoxLaunchOptions()` and `PlaywrightCrawler` configuration in `src/main.ts`. No new test dependencies are required.\n\n## Action\n1. **Open `test/main.test.ts`** and locate the existing test suite.\n2. **Add assertions** to verify that:\n   - The crawler does not throw errors related to stealth options.\n   - Dataset items are still produced with correct structure.\n   - Optionally (if feasible), check that page viewport is randomized by evaluating `{ width, height }` via `page.evaluate` and asserting the values are in a known set of common sizes.\n   - Confirm that timezone is applied by evaluating `Intl.DateTimeFormat().resolvedOptions().timeZone` and expecting `\"Europe/Rome\"`.\n   - Verify that the humanize option is enabled (this is hard to test directly; can be verified indirectly by checking that page interactions (e.g., click) work without failure).\n   - Confirm that resource blocking does not crash the page – the test should still navigate and extract data.\n3. **Preserve the existing basic crawling assertion** that dataset items contain `url` and `title`.\n4. **Update the test timeout** if needed, as stealth processing may add slight overhead.\n5. **Do not remove** the `purgeDefaultStorages()` call or `Actor` setup.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Integration tests guard against regressions when changing stealth internals.\n- Verifying viewport, timezone, and resource blocking concretely ensures the stealth configuration was applied correctly.\n- The test remains lightweight (single crawl of `apify.com`) and does not introduce external dependencies.\n- Adding a dedicated test case for stealth properties keeps the original flow test clean.\n\n## Implementation Details\n**Proposed test code additions** (inside existing `describe` block):\n\n```typescript\nimport { Page } from 'playwright';  // if not already imported\n\nit('should apply stealth settings: viewport, timezone, humanize, block noise', async () => {\n  // Existing crawler run already starts in the test; we need to access the page after navigation.\n  // Because crawler.run is already called, we can extract page info from the handling.\n  // However, the current test calls crawler.run and then expects dataset; we need to modify the handling.\n  // Option 1: enqueue a single request and capture the page in the handlePageFunction.\n  // The test already enqueues one request; we can add a custom handler to collect page info.\n  // Since the router is already configured, we can push custom data during the crawl.\n  // Simpler: evaluate page properties in a post-navigation hook? Not needed.\n  // We can add a custom request-specific check in the existing 'detail' handler:\n  //   const pageInfo = await page.evaluate(() => ({\n  //       width: window.innerWidth,\n  //       height: window.innerHeight,\n  //       timezone: Intl.DateTimeFormat().resolvedOptions().timeZone,\n  //   }));\n  //   await Actor.pushData({ ...pageInfo });\n  // Then after crawl, fetch dataset and assert those values.\n  // But modifying the handler would affect other tests. Better: add a separate test that runs a minimal crawl with a custom router.\n  // Given the scope, we can keep it simple: after the existing crawl, use the dataset to extract the pageInfo.\n  // For now, implement a lightweight assertion: verify that the crawler finished successfully and dataset length > 0.\n  // Viewport/timezone checks can be added as a separate `it` block using a custom crawler instance if desired.\n  // Since the step title says \"verify stealth enhancements don't break crawling\", the minimal pass is: no errors, data produced.\n  // We'll add both: a basic success check and a separate test for viewport/timezone (optional).\n});\n```\n\nGiven the instruction to be precise, I will implement the test as follows:\n\n```typescript\nit('should crawl successfully with stealth enhancements', async () => {\n  // The crawler already runs in beforeAll?\n  // Actually, the current test structure does the crawl inside it('should produce dataset items').\n  // We'll refactor to use beforeEach or separate it blocks.\n  // To avoid duplication, we keep the original test as is and add a new test that re-runs the crawl?\n  // Better: modify the original test to also verify stealth properties.\n  // I'll implement a simple addition: after dataset is retrieved, check that the page viewport and timezone were set correctly by evaluating them in a new handler.\n  // The cleanest approach: use the existing test but add a custom route handler for the first request to collect stealth info.\n  // However, the existing test uses the default router from routes.ts. We can override the router in the test by creating a new PlaywrightCrawler instance with a custom handler that pushes stealth info.\n  // Let's add a separate it block that creates a minimal crawler with custom options and checks viewport/timezone.\n});\n```\n\nAfter analysis, the most robust implementation is:\n- Keep the original test intact.\n- Add a new test case that creates a new `PlaywrightCrawler` instance (importing the same stealth launch options from `src/main.ts` or duplicating them), navigates to a single page, and uses `page.evaluate` to confirm viewport and timezone.\n- This new test should have a higher timeout (30s) and expect the dataset to contain the evaluated values.\n- Also assert that no `CORS` or `blocked` error occurred (resource blocking does not break navigation).\n\n**Code sketch for new test:**\n\n```typescript\nimport { PlaywrightCrawler } from '@crawlee/playwright';\nimport { camoufoxLaunchOptions } from 'camoufox-js';\n\nit('should apply viewport randomization and timezone', async () => {\n  await Actor.init();\n  const requestList = await RequestList.open('stealth-test', [\n    'https://httpbin.org/anything'\n  ]);\n  let stealthInfo: any = {};\n  const crawler = new PlaywrightCrawler({\n    maxRequestsPerCrawl: 1,\n    requestList,\n    launchContext: {\n      launchOptions: {\n        ...await camoufoxLaunchOptions({ headless: true, geoip: true, humanize: true, locale: 'it-IT', window: [1920, 1080], env: { TZ: 'Europe/Rome' } }),\n      },\n    },\n    preNavigationHooks: [async ({ page }) => {\n      await page.route('**/*', route => {\n        const url = route.request().url();\n        if (url.includes('google-analytics') || url.includes('doubleclick')) {\n          return route.abort();\n        }\n        return route.continue();\n      });\n    }],\n    async requestHandler({ page, request, log }) {\n      stealthInfo = await page.evaluate(() => ({\n        width: window.innerWidth,\n        height: window.innerHeight,\n        timezone: Intl.DateTimeFormat().resolvedOptions().timeZone,\n      }));\n    },\n  });\n  await crawler.run();\n  expect(stealthInfo.width).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(800);\n  expect(stealthInfo.timezone).toBe('Europe/Rome');\n  await Actor.exit();\n});\n```\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `page.evaluate` fails due to network error or page crash, the test should fail with clear error message.\n- If viewport size is not one of the expected common sizes, the test should still pass because random selection may produce a valid size — we only check it's within realistic bounds (width >= 800).\n- If timezone is overridden by geoip, the forced `TZ` env should take precedence; the test verifies it.\n- Resource blocking may cause some third-party scripts to fail; the test should ensure the page still loads main content (i.e., HTTP status 200).\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm test` locally or in CI; the new test must pass.\n- The original test must still pass.\n- Verify that the stealth options do not introduce any Playwright/Camoufox errors (e.g., invalid option types).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on the completion of steps: `set-timezone-locale`, `block-noise-resources`, `enable-humanize` (which modified `src/main.ts`).\n- No new npm packages.\n- Input schema unchanged.\n\n## Constraints\n- Must not break the existing basic crawling test.\n- The test must run within CI environment (Docker container with Playwright).\n- Use only Vitest and existing imports; avoid adding excessive dependencies.\n- Keep the test maintainable and focused on verifying stealth integration.\n\n## Additional Sections\n### API and Integration Impact\nThe test uses `Actor.init()` and `Actor.exit()` but does not rely on Apify platform storage – uses local memory dataset. The crawler configuration is independent of the main application to isolate stealth checks.\n\n### Performance and Scalability Notes\nThe additional test adds ~15-20s to total test duration (single page load). Acceptable for CI.\n\n### Documentation Impact\nUpdate any inline comments or test documentation to explain the purpose of stealth test.\n\n## Final Note\nImplement the test with actual code in `test/main.test.ts`. Ensure imports are added correctly. Escape any special characters in the prompt as standard JSON requires.",
